WEBVTT

00:02.461 --> 00:05.797
DRAGON:
In a land of myth and a time of magic...

00:05.964 --> 00:10.969
...the destiny of a great kingdom
rests on the shoulders of a young man.

00:11.136 --> 00:14.014
His name: Merlin.

00:17.726 --> 00:19.144
What's taking so long?

00:19.311 --> 00:22.231
MERLIN: It's the Feast of Beltane.
The king must look kingly.

00:22.397 --> 00:24.566
I'm hardly gonna look kingly
in my undergarments, am I?

00:24.733 --> 00:27.945
Have a little patience.
Think of something pleasant.

00:28.111 --> 00:31.907
-You in the stocks?
-Heh. Wait one second.

00:34.284 --> 00:35.827
One.

00:37.120 --> 00:38.330
What have you got there?

00:38.497 --> 00:40.791
Nothing. My hand. My other hand.

00:52.928 --> 00:54.721
Why are you putting another hole
in this belt?

00:54.888 --> 00:56.765
| was, uh...

00:56.932 --> 01:01.144
...enhancing it for comfort and ease of use.

01:01.311 --> 01:02.354
Are you saying I'm fat?

01:02.521 --> 01:05.524
No, I'm saying that the belt...

01:05.691 --> 01:07.734
...ils one hole shy of perfection.

01:07.901 --> 01:10.028
Ridiculous.

01:12.948 --> 01:14.449
[ARTHUR GRUNTS]

01:14.616 --> 01:16.243
Come on.

01:17.202 --> 01:20.539
Don't be too hard on yourself.
A little extra padding goes with the job...

01:20.706 --> 01:23.333
...what with all the feasts
and banquets and ceremonies.

01:23.500 --> 01:25.294
All right, Merlin, do what you have to do.

01:25.460 --> 01:27.504
-Not a word of this to anyone, understand?
-Trust me.

01:27.671 --> 01:31.675
If there's one thing I'm good at,
it's keeping secrets.

01:39.933 --> 01:41.935
[GUARDS COUGHING AND GROANING]

02:04.625 --> 02:07.294
-Have you seen Agravaine?
-Uh, no, sire. Not since this morning.

02:07.461 --> 02:09.378
ARTHUR:
Strange.

02:09.545 --> 02:11.923
He should be here by now.

02:14.301 --> 02:19.389
Ah, my favorite. Herb-crusted capon.

02:19.556 --> 02:22.017
Easy, now.
We don't want any more holes in that belt.

02:22.184 --> 02:23.352
[PERCIVAL SNORTS]

02:23.518 --> 02:25.020
[MERLIN & ARTHUR CHUCKLE]

02:25.729 --> 02:28.106
-Wine?
-Merlin.

02:30.942 --> 02:33.654
It's a good job you don't have anything
of any actual importance...

02:33.820 --> 02:35.822
...10 keep secret, isn't it?

03:06.561 --> 03:08.563
[CROWD CHATTERING AND LAUGHING]

03:12.150 --> 03:14.111
You all right?

03:14.736 --> 03:18.448
-No one likes to be called fat, Merlin.
-Sorry.

03:22.994 --> 03:24.246
It's Gwen, isn't it?

03:25.789 --> 03:29.251
| look for her in the room. She's not there.

03:32.462 --> 03:34.089
Then I remember why.

03:42.472 --> 03:43.640
[SIGHS]

03:45.600 --> 03:48.395
[SWORDS CLATTER]

04:18.675 --> 04:20.510
It's time.

04:52.834 --> 04:54.836
[CROWD SCREAMING]

04:55.462 --> 04:57.798
ELYAN:
Form a line to the well!

04:58.256 --> 05:00.217
We need more water. Now!

05:00.383 --> 05:02.636
-Forget about the water.
-But if we can't--

05:02.803 --> 05:04.513
[SOUTHRONS YELLING]

05:04.679 --> 05:06.181
ELYAN:
How did they breach the gate?

05:06.348 --> 05:08.892
We can't worry about that now.
Quickly, sound the alarm.

05:09.100 --> 05:10.644
[ALL YELLING]

05:18.485 --> 05:21.696
Sire, we're under attack.
They're within the city walls.

05:21.863 --> 05:23.198
[BELLS TOLLING]

05:23.365 --> 05:26.910
-Merlin, get everyone to the inner chamber.
-Yes, sire. Everyone follow me!

05:27.077 --> 05:29.371
Gwaine, secure the armory.
Percival, with me.

05:36.253 --> 05:38.630
-This is your doing.
-Oh, stand aside.

05:38.797 --> 05:42.676
-There's nothing you can do about it now.
- I can kill you for the traitor that you are.

05:43.343 --> 05:45.679
Brave words, Elyan.
And they shall be your last.

05:56.481 --> 05:59.484
We don't have time to play soldiers,
Agravaine.

06:17.252 --> 06:18.545
The lower town is lost.

06:18.712 --> 06:20.922
It's only a matter of time
before they reach the citadel.

06:21.089 --> 06:24.426
How did this happen?
How did they get in without being detected?

06:24.593 --> 06:26.845
[WHISPERING]
We knew Agravaine was planning something.

06:27.012 --> 06:29.514
It seems your worst fears
have been realized, Merlin.

06:31.600 --> 06:34.477
-Merlin?
-[IN NORMAL VOICE] I've got to find Arthur!

06:58.418 --> 07:00.420
[ALL YELLING]

07:06.676 --> 07:11.097
We can't hold them for much longer.
Lead the people to the woods.

07:12.057 --> 07:13.934
Retreat! Retreat!

07:14.100 --> 07:16.269
[ALL GRUNTING]

07:18.730 --> 07:20.690
[GROANING]

07:27.906 --> 07:29.366
ARTHUR:
Merlin.

07:29.532 --> 07:30.992
[ARTHUR GROANS]

07:31.159 --> 07:33.161
Been hiding in the broom cupboard
as usual, Merlin?

07:33.328 --> 07:35.080
We need to get out of here.

07:36.915 --> 07:37.958
[SPEAKS INCANTATION]

07:42.796 --> 07:43.964
[CROWD SCREAMING IN DISTANCE]

07:44.130 --> 07:47.258
-Are you all right?
-I'm fine.

07:48.551 --> 07:50.804
[ARTHUR GROANS]

07:51.846 --> 07:54.516
Maybe a broken rib or two.

08:10.865 --> 08:12.784
Agravaine.

08:23.128 --> 08:24.838
Don't. It's no good.

08:25.005 --> 08:27.298
Arthur, there are too many of them.

08:30.176 --> 08:32.886
We can deal with your uncle later.

08:33.513 --> 08:35.140
All right?

08:38.852 --> 08:39.894
Go.

08:40.102 --> 08:41.770
[ALL SHOUTING]

08:41.938 --> 08:46.359
Quickly, this way. Go on. Quickly, go on.

08:53.658 --> 08:55.702
The city has fallen.

08:57.037 --> 08:59.789
Camelot is ours.

08:59.956 --> 09:01.916
And?

09:04.419 --> 09:08.381
Taking Camelot was the easy part, Helios.

09:08.548 --> 09:10.508
| want Arthur.

09:11.092 --> 09:12.677
Where is he?

09:12.886 --> 09:16.097
He's right here, my lady, in the palace.

09:18.725 --> 09:21.102
He has nowhere left to run.

09:22.228 --> 09:23.480
Hmm.

09:26.524 --> 09:28.068
[CHUCKLES]

09:30.028 --> 09:33.907
| can bind the rib cage, but even then,
we run the risk of puncturing a lung.

09:34.074 --> 09:37.202
Do whatever it takes, Gaius,
just so long as I can swing a sword.

09:37.368 --> 09:39.370
[CROWD SHOUTING]

09:40.163 --> 09:42.040
GAIUS: How do we stand?
-The citadel is overrun.

09:42.207 --> 09:43.625
We can't hold on much longer.

09:43.792 --> 09:46.419
-How long before they reach us?
-Minutes at best.

09:46.586 --> 09:48.713
They're coming for Arthur. They'll kill him.

09:48.880 --> 09:52.342
-We must get him to safety while we still can.
-Arthur would never abandon his people.

09:52.509 --> 09:53.843
[POUNDING ON DOOR]

09:54.010 --> 09:56.262
GWAINE:
He'd rather die.

09:56.429 --> 09:59.265
Barricade the doors.
Give us as much time as you can.

10:01.559 --> 10:03.603
We need to get Arthur out
whether he likes it or not.

10:03.770 --> 10:05.814
Give him some potion,
something to knock him out.

10:05.980 --> 10:07.440
| don't have anything strong enough.

10:07.607 --> 10:11.277
In my chambers perhaps,
but the Southrons have control of the palace.

10:13.196 --> 10:16.282
-There must be something.
-I'm sorry, Merlin.

10:17.033 --> 10:21.079
Maybe there's something you can do.
Arthur won't go willingly.

10:21.246 --> 10:23.581
But what if he was to lose his will?

10:25.125 --> 10:27.293
Are you suggesting magic?

10:27.961 --> 10:30.338
-Can you do it?
-I can try.

10:35.635 --> 10:38.471
-I'm sorry, sir. This is going to hurt.
-Just get on with it.

10:38.638 --> 10:40.473
[ARTHUR GROANS
& MERLIN SPEAKS INCANTATION]

10:50.108 --> 10:51.526
[POUNDING ON DOOR]

10:52.527 --> 10:54.362
We need to leave now, sire.

10:57.740 --> 10:59.576
Of course.

11:06.124 --> 11:07.417
Then let's go.

11:07.625 --> 11:08.668
[POUNDING ON DOOR]

11:08.835 --> 11:10.712
We'll use the postern gate.

11:14.132 --> 11:17.135
GWAINE:
I'll keep them off your back as long as I can.

11:25.768 --> 11:28.938
-Gather your things, Gaius.
-You go, Merlin. I'll just slow you down.

11:29.105 --> 11:31.816
-Gaius, no.
-You must know it's for the best.

11:31.983 --> 11:35.445
-No, if you stay here--
GWAINE: No time to argue. I'm sorry.

11:36.404 --> 11:39.199
Look after our king, Merlin.

11:39.949 --> 11:41.951
[POUNDING ON DOOR]

11:51.920 --> 11:53.922
[ALL YELLING]

12:00.261 --> 12:02.931
It seems your victory is short-lived, Morgana.

12:05.934 --> 12:09.520
Prepare the horses. We're going on a hunt.

12:12.899 --> 12:14.484
Thank you, Percival.

12:15.193 --> 12:16.236
Can you walk on your own?

12:16.402 --> 12:19.113
-Oh, yes. Just point me in the right direction.
-Shh.

12:19.280 --> 12:20.490
[FOOTSTEPS APPROACHING]

12:20.657 --> 12:22.075
[ELYAN GRUNTS]

12:22.242 --> 12:25.286
-Elyan.
-Heh. Don't hold back on my account.

12:26.579 --> 12:28.748
-Is the way out of Camelot clear?
-As far as I can tell.

12:37.465 --> 12:39.300
Come on, Arthur.

12:48.601 --> 12:50.853
PERCIVAL:
They'll come after us. They know Arthur's alive.

12:51.020 --> 12:54.732
Then we have to make it across the border,
find sanctuary anywhere we can.

12:54.899 --> 12:58.444
| know a place. Ealdor.
It's beyond the White Mountain.

12:58.611 --> 12:59.737
Wait.

13:01.531 --> 13:03.491
[HORSES GALLOPING IN DISTANCE]

13:03.658 --> 13:05.243
Listen.

13:08.830 --> 13:10.456
PERCIVAL:
Run!

13:26.097 --> 13:27.932
[SPEAKS INCANTATION]

13:37.108 --> 13:38.359
[ARTHUR GRUNTS]

13:41.946 --> 13:43.865
Where's Percival?

13:45.116 --> 13:47.118
We have to go.

13:52.665 --> 13:54.792
-Go.
-What about you?

13:54.959 --> 13:57.712
Don't worry about me. Go.

13:57.920 --> 13:59.380
[YELLING]

13:59.589 --> 14:01.341
[ALL GRUNTING]

14:10.641 --> 14:12.018
[ARTHUR GRUNTS]

14:12.185 --> 14:15.021
Sorry. My fault.

14:18.816 --> 14:21.861
Well, I think we're safe for now.

14:24.739 --> 14:28.868
But we need to find you some kind of disguise.
You're too conspicuous in those clothes.

14:29.035 --> 14:32.205
Whatever you say. I'm entirely in your hands.

14:43.549 --> 14:45.551
All quarters of Camelot
are now under our control.

14:46.469 --> 14:50.056
Some knights have fled to the woods,
but those that did not escape...

14:50.223 --> 14:52.183
...are either in our dungeons or dead.

14:52.350 --> 14:53.476
Very good.

14:57.021 --> 14:59.857
Have the people of Camelot welcomed me
as their queen?

15:00.441 --> 15:03.694
They will swear allegiance
to no one but Arthur.

15:05.113 --> 15:07.156
| expected no less.

15:08.032 --> 15:09.784
Burn their crops.

15:12.412 --> 15:14.956
Let's see how they feel
when their children begin to starve.

15:16.499 --> 15:17.625
And what of Arthur?

15:35.184 --> 15:37.603
We'll find Arthur soon enough.

15:43.359 --> 15:46.237
MERLIN:
Ah. Perfect.

15:55.621 --> 15:58.541
-In your own time, obviously.
ARTHUR: Unh.

15:58.708 --> 16:00.334
Sorry, Merlin.

16:00.501 --> 16:03.963
Some of these things
are a little on the tight side.

16:04.922 --> 16:09.010
-Beggars can't be choosers, sire.
-No, you're right.

16:09.177 --> 16:12.430
| probably should learn to think
before I speak, shouldn't I?

16:13.181 --> 16:17.351
-It would be a start.
-Unh. All done.

16:18.102 --> 16:19.145
[GRUNTS]

16:23.483 --> 16:25.276
[MERLIN LAUGHS]

16:25.443 --> 16:28.821
Well, Arthur, what can I say?

16:30.239 --> 16:32.033
You look like a total turnip-head.

16:34.744 --> 16:37.246
Well, shall I try something else?
There's plenty more here.

16:37.413 --> 16:39.665
No, no. That will do absolutely fine.

16:39.832 --> 16:43.127
-Although maybe I'll take that.
-My gold?

16:43.294 --> 16:45.588
-Probably safer with me.
-Of course.

16:53.804 --> 16:55.139
MORGANA:
Do you know what this is?

16:55.306 --> 16:56.641
[HISSING]

16:58.601 --> 16:59.810
No?

17:00.895 --> 17:04.982
It's a Nathair,
from the Mountains of Asgorath.

17:05.148 --> 17:06.526
Harmless enough most of the time.

17:06.692 --> 17:10.780
But with a little persuasion,
it can cause a man pain beyond all imagining.

17:10.988 --> 17:12.823
[NATHAIR HISSES]

17:12.990 --> 17:14.242
MORGANA:
So you have a choice.

17:15.742 --> 17:16.993
Tell me where Arthur is...

17:19.872 --> 17:22.458
...or sample the delights
of my little friend here.

17:22.625 --> 17:24.585
I'll tell you nothing.

17:25.294 --> 17:27.463
| was hoping you'd say that.

17:32.677 --> 17:35.721
[SPEAKING INCANTATION]

17:45.439 --> 17:47.817
[ELYAN SCREAMING]

17:48.025 --> 17:50.027
[ELYAN CONTINUES SCREAMING]

17:51.821 --> 17:54.490
Good God, will it never end?

17:55.324 --> 17:57.368
What's wrong?

17:57.535 --> 17:58.703
Don't have the stomach for it?

17:58.869 --> 18:00.329
[DOOR OPENS]

18:01.414 --> 18:03.124
MORGANA:
Arthur travels to Ealdor.

18:03.291 --> 18:06.877
You will leave without delay.
And, Agravaine...

18:08.754 --> 18:13.175
...fail me again
and you'll be taking Elyan's place.

18:38.242 --> 18:41.996
GWAINE: What have they done to him?
GAIUS: This is the work of the Nathair serpent.

18:42.163 --> 18:45.249
He's been tortured to the limit
of human endurance.

18:45.416 --> 18:46.542
Can you help him?

18:48.002 --> 18:49.754
I'll do what I can.

18:53.966 --> 18:56.135
[FOOTSTEPS APPROACHING]

18:59.347 --> 19:02.350
- I thought I told you to leave at once.
-My men are all ready to depart.

19:02.516 --> 19:03.934
Then what are you waiting for?

19:07.271 --> 19:08.731
I——

19:09.732 --> 19:11.942
| just wanted to say goodbye.

19:13.235 --> 19:14.612
Consider it done.

19:16.155 --> 19:18.741
And to ask you to take care.

19:21.118 --> 19:22.995
Why?

19:23.162 --> 19:24.955
| have nothing to fear.

19:25.122 --> 19:30.795
Despite all that you have achieved, Morgana,
you must remain cautious.

19:30.961 --> 19:33.130
There's danger at every turn.

19:35.883 --> 19:39.261
You can trust no one, not even Helios.

19:40.179 --> 19:42.640
No one except you. Is that it?

19:42.807 --> 19:45.059
| am your one true ally, my lady.

19:46.977 --> 19:49.730
| am your one true friend.

19:52.566 --> 19:54.902
| would do anything for you.

19:55.528 --> 19:58.656
-You know that.
- I am grateful for your loyalty, Agravaine.

20:00.533 --> 20:03.285
That is why
| have entrusted this mission to you.

20:05.371 --> 20:07.998
| understand. Of course I do.

20:08.165 --> 20:10.835
| only wish it did not take me
from your side...

20:11.001 --> 20:12.837
...where I can best protect you.

20:13.796 --> 20:15.756
Find Arthur...

20:15.923 --> 20:18.801
...and you need never leave my side again.

20:21.929 --> 20:23.931
My lady.

20:44.577 --> 20:46.036
Stop.

20:48.873 --> 20:52.501
Wait here.

21:10.352 --> 21:11.562
Hello.

21:15.608 --> 21:18.027
| found them lurking in the woods.

21:23.240 --> 21:24.867
See anything interesting?

21:26.619 --> 21:28.120
No.

21:30.414 --> 21:32.416
You wanna watch
where you stick your beak, boy.

21:32.583 --> 21:34.919
| didn't see anything.
We were just passing through.

21:35.085 --> 21:39.381
-They've no horses, no supplies, nothing.
-Like to travel light, do you?

21:40.174 --> 21:41.675
Something like that.

21:41.884 --> 21:44.845
-So where you headed?
-North over the border.

21:45.012 --> 21:46.388
Lot's kingdom.

21:47.139 --> 21:49.600
He doesn't take kindly to strangers,
| can tell you.

21:50.267 --> 21:52.478
Likes to decorate his fortress
with their heads.

21:52.645 --> 21:55.439
-So why are you heading there?
- I have my reasons.

21:56.273 --> 21:57.775
Right.

21:59.485 --> 22:00.653
| agree with him.

22:01.654 --> 22:02.863
What's wrong with your friend?

22:03.572 --> 22:05.825
He's a simpleton. He can't help it.

22:05.991 --> 22:08.410
-Look after him, do you?
-Without me, he wouldn't last a day.

22:15.167 --> 22:17.795
Very well.
| suppose you can be on your way.

22:22.550 --> 22:24.343
Could we not come with you?

22:26.971 --> 22:30.057
| mean, I would be grateful
for the company, to be honest.

22:30.558 --> 22:32.434
I'm very annoying.

22:32.601 --> 22:34.019
-Sorry.
MERLIN: Please?

22:34.186 --> 22:37.273
Don't push it, boy.
You're lucky I let you go with your lives.

22:37.439 --> 22:38.649
| could pay you.

22:40.359 --> 22:41.402
With gold.

22:45.155 --> 22:48.033
Well, why didn't you say so before?

22:51.078 --> 22:52.121
ARTHUR:
Mm.

23:02.006 --> 23:05.259
What kind of coward would deny who he is?

23:06.051 --> 23:10.890
Men, this way. They can't have gone far.

23:25.237 --> 23:27.114
TRISTAN:
We make camp here.

23:33.913 --> 23:36.624
-Why, thank you.
-My pleasure.

24:03.984 --> 24:06.028
ISOLDE:
That doesn't concern you.

24:06.862 --> 24:08.822
Oh, I'm sorry.
It's just I recognized that smell.

24:08.989 --> 24:11.867
-That is frankincense, isn't it?
-What if it is?

24:13.202 --> 24:16.789
-Must be worth a fortune.
-It must be.

24:19.416 --> 24:22.461
-You're smugglers?
-We prefer to think of it as free trade.

24:22.628 --> 24:25.631
TRISTAN: Heh.
MERLIN: It's forbidden by edict of the king.

24:25.798 --> 24:30.302
-If you're caught, you could be killed.
-Caught? Tristan and Isolde?

24:30.469 --> 24:32.096
| don't think so.

24:32.262 --> 24:37.101
We're too quick and too smart
for the half-wit king in Camelot.

24:40.145 --> 24:41.188
You don't say.

24:41.897 --> 24:43.065
[CLICKS TONGUE]

24:56.662 --> 24:58.414
More soup?

24:58.956 --> 25:00.916
Yes, please.

25:06.630 --> 25:08.340
Thank you.

25:09.133 --> 25:12.678
A "please" and a "thank you"
all at the same time. That's amazing.

25:17.516 --> 25:19.643
-Is it?
-Mm.

25:20.519 --> 25:24.606
Well, let's just say manners
are not your strong point.

25:25.190 --> 25:26.942
Really?

25:27.609 --> 25:29.445
In what way?

25:29.611 --> 25:33.157
Rude, thoughtless, insensitive.

25:33.323 --> 25:36.827
-And that's when you're in a good mood.
-I'm sorry to hear that.

25:40.372 --> 25:42.958
| don't think you realize
how hard I work for you.

25:43.125 --> 25:46.754
| know you're the king, but it would be nice
if you could do one small thing for yourself...

25:46.920 --> 25:50.507
...as a gesture, mark of respect.

25:50.674 --> 25:53.802
Sorry to have been a disappointment, Merlin.

25:56.263 --> 25:57.848
I'll try harder in future.

25:58.891 --> 26:00.768
Oh, I look forward to that.

26:03.979 --> 26:05.606
On the other hand, why wait?

26:06.899 --> 26:10.527
-That pot will need rinsing out as well.
-Of course.

26:10.694 --> 26:13.113
And when you're done with that,
the horses need a rubdown too.

26:13.280 --> 26:15.741
My pleasure.

26:21.747 --> 26:23.040
Over there.

26:27.503 --> 26:29.505
[POTS CLANGING]

26:33.133 --> 26:36.261
MERLIN: You all right?
ARTHUR: Yeah.

27:08.669 --> 27:11.755
You'd better have a damn good
explanation for this, Merlin.

27:11.922 --> 27:13.799
Fine. I'll just carry on kicking you.

27:13.966 --> 27:15.968
[GRUNTING]

27:18.804 --> 27:20.973
-You're back.
-What do you mean I'm back?

27:21.140 --> 27:22.516
You're talking gibberish.

27:22.683 --> 27:25.435
Listen to me, please. Camelot is lost.

27:25.602 --> 27:29.940
You were injured in an attack.
You passed out. I had to get you out of there.

27:32.067 --> 27:33.110
Where are we now?

27:34.027 --> 27:37.781
We're heading north to a safe haven,
to Ealdor.

27:37.948 --> 27:40.826
Hopefully, the knights will meet us there.

27:40.993 --> 27:43.036
Who are these people?

27:44.121 --> 27:45.914
They're, uh...

27:46.707 --> 27:47.749
...smugglers.

27:47.916 --> 27:50.419
-Smugglers!
-Shh.

27:51.211 --> 27:53.797
All right, let's assume for one moment
you know what you're doing.

27:53.964 --> 27:57.301
-It doesn't explain why I look like a village idiot.
-It's the perfect disguise.

27:58.343 --> 28:02.514
No one would ever suspect you of being,
you know, who you are.

28:02.681 --> 28:07.102
I'm sorry, Merlin.
| am not going around looking like this.

28:07.269 --> 28:09.688
You have to. You've got to keep in character.

28:09.855 --> 28:11.773
Character?

28:11.940 --> 28:14.193
-What character?
TRISTAN: You.

28:15.110 --> 28:18.071
We leave as soon as the horses are watered.

28:18.238 --> 28:20.866
Explain it to the simpleton, would you?

28:34.379 --> 28:35.923
Simpleton.

28:36.089 --> 28:38.091
-He's talking to you.
- I don't answer to that name.

28:38.258 --> 28:39.968
You're in character, remember.

28:41.345 --> 28:43.764
Impressive piece.

28:46.808 --> 28:48.560
[IN RUSTIC ACCENT]
Thankee, sir.

28:48.727 --> 28:50.229
May 17

28:54.733 --> 28:56.068
[TRISTAN EXHALES]

28:56.235 --> 28:58.111
Magnificent.

28:58.278 --> 29:02.282
The only place you find workmanship
of this quality...

29:02.449 --> 29:04.409
...Is the royal forge of Camelot.

29:04.868 --> 29:05.994
Tell me...

29:07.579 --> 29:08.830
...how did you come by it?

29:09.289 --> 29:11.708
| won it in a card game.

29:11.875 --> 29:15.545
| gave it to him as a present.
He won't be parted from it.

29:15.712 --> 29:17.005
Makes him feel safe.

29:22.219 --> 29:24.429
TRISTAN:
| hope for your sake that's true.

29:24.596 --> 29:27.182
I'd hate to think that I was riding
with a knight of Camelot.

29:29.851 --> 29:31.728
Aye.

29:33.480 --> 29:34.523
[ISOLDE CHUCKLES]

29:34.690 --> 29:36.817
Knight of Camelot?

29:37.025 --> 29:38.485
MERLIN: Ha, ha.
ISOLDE: Look at him.

29:38.652 --> 29:39.695
TRISTAN:
You're right.

29:39.861 --> 29:44.157
The knights may be stupid,
but they're not that stupid.

29:44.908 --> 29:46.910
[ARTHUR & MERLIN CHUCKLING]

29:48.287 --> 29:50.163
Pack your things, simpleton.

29:50.330 --> 29:52.749
[IN NORMAL VOICE]
Call me that again and I'll run you through.

29:52.916 --> 29:55.669
-We won't have to keep it up for much longer.
-How long?

29:55.836 --> 29:57.754
[MAN GROANS]

29:57.963 --> 29:59.214
[ALL YELLING]

30:02.759 --> 30:04.386
Stay close.

30:15.355 --> 30:16.940
Head for those trees. We'll cover you.

30:18.692 --> 30:19.735
Do you wanna live or not?

30:25.532 --> 30:27.659
[MEN GROAN]

30:31.621 --> 30:35.292
-Now what?
-Now it's our turn.

30:35.459 --> 30:37.753
-Who's gonna cover us?
-Don't be a simpleton, Merlin.

30:53.018 --> 30:55.270
ISOLDE: They haven't found the cargo.
TRISTAN: They will.

30:55.437 --> 30:59.066
Besides, they weren't after the cargo.
They were after you.

30:59.232 --> 31:01.401
Who the hell are you?

31:01.568 --> 31:05.655
My name is Arthur Pendragon.

31:06.156 --> 31:09.826
TRISTAN: The king of Camelot?
-At least, I was.

31:09.993 --> 31:12.704
I've lost everything I've worked for
for some good-for-nothing king?

31:12.871 --> 31:14.623
That's something coming from a smuggler.

31:14.790 --> 31:17.876
| wouldn't have to be a smuggler
if it wasn't for your damn taxes, would |?

31:18.043 --> 31:20.170
Those taxes help protect the people
of this land.

31:20.337 --> 31:22.464
TRISTAN:
My people are dead. You call that protection?

31:22.631 --> 31:24.883
Excuse me. Sorry to interrupt, but:

31:25.050 --> 31:27.052
[SOUTHRONS YELLING]

31:29.888 --> 31:31.765
[ALL GRUNTING]

31:44.486 --> 31:45.821
[GROANS]

31:53.245 --> 31:54.287
Isolde.

31:57.249 --> 31:59.793
We had a deal. Partners for life, remember?

32:01.044 --> 32:02.379
[WINCES]

32:02.546 --> 32:04.631
When have I not kept my promises?

32:05.924 --> 32:08.510
We need to keep moving.
There'll be more coming soon.

32:08.677 --> 32:11.972
Then go. There's nothing stopping you.

32:12.889 --> 32:16.685
-Come with us to Ealdor. You'll be safe there.
-I'm choosy about the company I keep.

32:18.353 --> 32:20.439
He saved my life, Tristan.

32:22.774 --> 32:24.317
Thank you.

32:24.484 --> 32:27.654
TRISTAN: But none of this
would have happened if it wasn't for them.

32:28.572 --> 32:31.491
She's injured. She needs shelter and rest.

32:31.700 --> 32:33.118
[SIGHS]

32:37.789 --> 32:39.332
Mm.

32:40.041 --> 32:41.168
Very well.

32:41.960 --> 32:46.089
But know this, Arthur Pendragon.
| do this for her.

32:46.256 --> 32:49.885
You and your kind bring nothing
but misery to this land.

32:57.142 --> 32:59.686
Have you come to gloat, my lady?

32:59.853 --> 33:02.689
Is that any way to treat an old friend?

33:02.856 --> 33:05.567
Oh, I'll forgive you.
After all, you're not looking your best.

33:06.443 --> 33:08.028
GWAINE:
Can't you see he's starving?

33:09.446 --> 33:11.031
-We all are.
MORGANA: Of course you are.

33:11.615 --> 33:13.074
You killed so many of my men.

33:15.118 --> 33:17.370
I'll have the kitchen prepare you a feast.

33:17.579 --> 33:19.581
[CHAINS CLANKING]

33:29.758 --> 33:34.346
| think not of myself but of Gaius.

33:35.096 --> 33:36.473
He can't survive long without food.

33:36.640 --> 33:38.850
[SCOFFS]

33:39.017 --> 33:41.353
Oh, Gwaine.

33:43.897 --> 33:45.690
So handsome...

33:45.857 --> 33:48.527
...So selfless.

33:49.236 --> 33:50.946
Of course, you shall have some supper.

33:53.073 --> 33:55.242
As long as you're prepared to sing for it.

34:17.222 --> 34:21.685
This marks the border
between Camelot and Lot's kingdom.

34:21.851 --> 34:24.437
Ealdor lies at the far side of that valley.

34:24.603 --> 34:27.357
-Maybe half a day on foot.
-We'll rest here for the night.

34:27.524 --> 34:30.318
There's no way Agravaine could have
tracked us through those mountains.

34:30.485 --> 34:32.987
I'll make a fire. We must keep Isolde warm.

34:37.117 --> 34:41.121
-Here. Keep your strength up.
-I'll get my own.

34:46.167 --> 34:48.628
[CROWD JEERING]

34:56.261 --> 34:59.764
Behold! A knight of Camelot.

35:00.682 --> 35:04.060
Famed as the greatest knights
in five kingdoms.

35:05.604 --> 35:08.064
Let's see if that fame's deserved, shall we?

35:13.737 --> 35:15.739
[CROWD SHOUTING]

35:22.954 --> 35:24.956
[ROARING]

35:30.629 --> 35:31.671
ARTHUR;:
You knew?

35:34.633 --> 35:36.968
You knew Agravaine was betraying me?

35:38.595 --> 35:40.639
| couldn't be sure.

35:40.805 --> 35:43.767
But, um, I did have my suspicions.

35:45.310 --> 35:47.812
| feel like such a fool.

35:48.480 --> 35:50.065
| put such trust in him.

35:53.652 --> 35:56.446
All this time, I was blind to his treachery
as I was to Morgana's.

35:56.613 --> 35:59.741
You were deceived, Arthur.
It could happen to anyone.

35:59.908 --> 36:01.618
Yet it keeps happening to me.

36:04.871 --> 36:07.248
| cared about these people. I...

36:07.415 --> 36:09.793
| don't understand.

36:11.711 --> 36:13.421
What have I done wrong?
Why do they hate me?

36:13.588 --> 36:17.592
No, they don't hate you.
They just crave your power for themselves.

36:18.093 --> 36:19.552
Perhaps.

36:20.220 --> 36:22.972
Would they still want that power
if I was the king my people deserve?

36:23.139 --> 36:26.476
-Maybe Tristan is right.
-Tristan was angry and...

36:27.811 --> 36:30.021
...afraid.

36:30.188 --> 36:33.983
He needed to blame someone.
But it's not you that's to blame.

36:37.779 --> 36:39.155
You seem very sure about all this.

36:39.322 --> 36:42.033
All' I know is that, for your many faults...

36:42.200 --> 36:44.619
...you are honest and brave and truehearted.

36:46.413 --> 36:50.041
And one day you will be the greatest king
this land has ever known.

36:57.257 --> 36:58.591
[SCOFFS]

37:01.094 --> 37:02.137
Well...

37:04.973 --> 37:07.308
...good to know I have the support
of my servant, at least.

37:07.475 --> 37:09.227
I'm not alone.

37:12.063 --> 37:13.857
Believe me.

37:22.824 --> 37:24.075
[CROWD SHOUTING]

37:25.535 --> 37:26.745
[GWAINE & MAN GRUNTING]

37:47.223 --> 37:51.144
Is that all you have?
| was promised a decent fight.

37:57.776 --> 38:00.487
You're a very angry man. I can see that.

38:01.070 --> 38:03.239
It must be hard being so ugly.

38:06.075 --> 38:08.620
Children crying, women screaming.

38:12.123 --> 38:13.333
Come on.

38:36.105 --> 38:37.774
[MAN GROWLS]

38:40.693 --> 38:42.028
[MAN GROANS]

38:52.872 --> 38:55.708
MORGANA: Congratulations, Sir Knight.
An admirable display.

38:56.709 --> 38:59.254
You've earned your reward.

39:01.965 --> 39:04.300
But you're going to have to do better
if you want some more.

39:04.467 --> 39:06.511
[CROWD CHUCKLES]

39:11.850 --> 39:13.142
[CROWD CHEERING]

39:28.199 --> 39:29.659
Merlin.

39:30.660 --> 39:32.287
Mother.

39:36.916 --> 39:39.168
Welcome home, Merlin.

39:39.377 --> 39:41.337
[CHUCKLES]

39:46.009 --> 39:47.844
Cleaned her wound.
There's no sign of infection.

39:48.928 --> 39:51.055
So as long as she gets plenty of rest,
she'll be fine.

39:51.222 --> 39:54.601
Thank you, Merlin,
for everything you've done for her.

40:01.190 --> 40:05.570
I'm sorry I've brought this misfortune
upon you.

40:07.363 --> 40:09.824
Well, I may have lost my cargo...

40:10.742 --> 40:13.244
...but I still have my beloved Isolde.

40:17.624 --> 40:19.876
Then you're richer than you know.

40:43.066 --> 40:46.277
Spread out.
Ensure the village is surrounded.

40:47.987 --> 40:50.239
No one must escape.

40:51.449 --> 40:54.494
-It's good to have you home, Merlin.
-I'm so sorry it's been so long.

40:54.661 --> 40:58.915
| understand how it is, your life in Camelot.

40:59.457 --> 41:02.502
| worry about you sometimes.
The dangers you must face.

41:02.669 --> 41:04.420
Mother, I don't want you to worry.

41:04.587 --> 41:10.468
- I can't help it. It's what mothers do.
-Well, we are safe here, all of us.

41:12.428 --> 41:14.263
How's she been?

41:14.430 --> 41:19.978
As well as can be expected,
but, um, a broken heart takes time to mend.

41:21.479 --> 41:23.189
Yeah.

41:43.084 --> 41:44.419
Guinevere.

41:46.087 --> 41:48.297
Hello, Arthur.

41:54.095 --> 41:56.264
What are you doing here?

41:58.558 --> 42:00.852
It's as good a place as any.

42:07.442 --> 42:09.318
I've missed you.

42:10.695 --> 42:12.697
And I you.

42:37.889 --> 42:39.891
[CROWD SCREAMING]

42:46.606 --> 42:47.940
MERLIN:
Agravaine.

42:49.317 --> 42:50.610
He's found us.

42:52.862 --> 42:54.864
[CROWD SCREAMING]

43:03.498 --> 43:06.459
-Any suggestions?
-Round the back.

43:19.764 --> 43:21.474
[SPEAKS INCANTATION]

43:29.190 --> 43:30.525
[GRUNTS]

43:33.111 --> 43:35.947
There! Get them!

43:50.086 --> 43:52.088
ANNOUNCER:
Merlin.

43:59.595 --> 44:01.514
You have magic.

44:58.738 --> 45:00.740
[English - US - SDH]
